******
[2]
Date: Sat 19 Jul 2014
Source: Biosecurity Queensland media release [edited]
http://www.daff.qld.gov.au/services/news-and-updates/biosecurity/news/new-hendra-virus-case-confirmed-in-gladstone-area


Biosecurity Queensland has quarantined a property in the Gladstone area after a deceased horse tested positive for Hendra virus [HeV] infection. Chief veterinary officer Dr Allison Crook said the horse had been unwell for a number of days and was found dead on Thursday [17 Jul 2014]. "The positive test result was received last night," Dr Crook said.

"Tracing and exposure assessments are being undertaken on other horses that may have had contact with the infected horse to determine if further testing needs to be done. The property has been quarantined, which means restrictions apply to moving horses and horse materials on and off the property. The quarantine will be in place for at least one month." Queensland Health is following up all human contacts. At this stage, it appears no one is at serious risk.

Dr Crook said this was the 3rd case of Hendra virus in Queensland this year [2014]. "Hendra virus infection can occur throughout the year, so it's important that horse owners take steps to protect themselves and their animals at all times," she said. "The affected horse had not been vaccinated. Vaccination is the single most effective way of reducing the risk of HeV infection in horses. It is recommended that horse owners speak to their veterinarian about vaccinating their horses. If a horse becomes sick, owners should contact their veterinarian immediately. People in contact with horses need to remember to continue to practise good biosecurity and personal hygiene measures even if a horse is vaccinated against HeV."

For more information on prevention of HeV or biosecurity steps in an incident, visit http://www.biosecurity.qld.gov.au or call 13 25 23. For information on the vaccine, visit http://www.health4horses.com.au.

