[The importance of horse vaccination in Australia against HeV to protect the horses and human contacts against this zoonotic disease, which is regarded lethal for humans, has been discussed in previous postings.

Information on a commercially available vaccine which was launched in November 2012 and is currently available nationwide through accredited veterinarians is included in "Your Hendra virus vaccine - questions answered", available at http://www.horsecouncil.org.au/ahic/index.cfm/alerts/updated-information-about-the-new-hendra-vaccine-pdf/.

According to the said publication, "on average, the cost of the vaccine is not more than the cost of a shoeing."

A comprehensive overview on Hendra virus and its close relative, Nipah virus (NiV), is available in chapter 2.9.6, Hendra and Nipah virus diseases, of OIE's Terrestrial Manual, at http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Health_standards/tahm/2.09.06_HENDRA_&_NIPAH_FINAL.pdf (updated 2010).

Hendra virus is classified in a new genus, _Henipavirus_, in the subfamily Paramyxovirinae. HeV (and NiV) are biosafety level 4 agents. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2626012,186.]
